##ZOONOSIS: How did the virus get into humans?

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

Zoonosis is a new and very dangerous infectious disease in modern society. These viruses (bacteria) usually hide in animals, constantly carrying out gene mutation and gene recombination, looking for opportunities to invade human beings.

The mainstream view of the scientific community that the source of new crown and SARS from bats, the two epidemic situation is very similar, can learn from each other. In this paper, we try to do some simple analysis of the SARS epidemic in that year, and combine with the theory of evolution to explain the basic characteristics of the new coronavirus, hoping to help everyone understand the necessity of the national epidemic prevention policy, and reduce unnecessary panic.

By Yuan Yue

How is SARS under control?

SARS broke out at the end of 2002 and ended in July 2003. It lasted for more than half a year. This speed is very fast in the history of the struggle between human beings and infectious diseases, especially for respiratory infectious diseases. There are three main reasons:

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In May 2003, Beijing Xiaotangshan Hospital was built to treat SARS patients.

1. SARS (and its new crown) are both RNA viruses. RNA molecules are unstable, easily degraded and do not live long in host cells, so patients infected with RNA viruses usually have only two outcomes: either they are completely cured, and the virus disappears completely; Either the patient dies, the virus disappears completely, and there's basically no other option. There are exceptions to this rule, more on that later

2. RNA replication error rate is much higher than DNA, so the RNA virus mutation rate is very high, this is RNA virus more difficult to deal with the main reason. But SARS virus RNA comes with an error correction mechanism, the mutation rate is lower, coupled with the SARS virus is a single-stranded RNA, less prone to gene recombination. In contrast, the influenza genome contains eight small RNA molecules that can be easily interchanged and randomly assembled into a new influenza virus if a host cell is infected with two influenza viruses, that's why flu viruses mutate so easily, and why flu vaccines are reissued every year.

Subsequent studies have shown that the SARS virus has undergone very few mutations throughout the epidemic and has not affected the basic nature of the virus, making it much easier to deal with. The good news is that the new coronavirus and the SARS virus are very similar, and their mutation rates should be very similar.

Community isolation point virus nucleic acid detection. (photo by expedition)

3. SARS infected people are basically not contagious until they have symptoms, so the epidemic prevention department should only keep a close watch on the floating population and isolate all the patients with fever, which greatly reduces the workload. It would have been much more expensive to quarantine all those who had been there, and the epidemic would not have ended so quickly.

So far, asymptomatic cases of new Crown Infections have been reported by scientists in China, Germany and Japan, but Germany has just corrected the paper because the authors did not visit patients directly, just interviewing four people who had been in contact with the patient led to the conclusion that the infection was asymptomatic. But when the scientists interviewed the patient, they found that the patient was actually showing symptoms that the people around him just didn't see, which was even better news.

Of course, this correction does not prove that the new coronavirus must not be able to achieve asymptomatic transmission, but from the current situation, this situation, if there is, the probability is very low, and asymptomatic people will not be very high capacity for infection, nothing to worry about just yet. In addition, if there is a large number of asymptomatic infections, then the new coronavirus is very low toxicity. In a way, that's good news.

Expedition photography

In fact, whether there is asymptomatic transmission of the new coronavirus is very important, even can be said to be the most important point of the epidemic prevention work. Because if asymptomatic infection becomes the norm, it means that the current policy of mass isolation will last for a long time, and not only the common people are likely to be overwhelmed, but the impact on the Chinese economy will also be huge.

Summary: The SARS epidemic came and ended quickly, which is a great feat accomplished by all mankind, and fully demonstrated the power of modern medicine. If this outbreak had occurred in ancient times, the consequences would have been unimaginable. But because the epidemic ended so quickly, and because new drugs and vaccines were developed so slowly, they did little to help, the disease still killed many people. In the future, we'll have to work faster to keep up with the virus.

Why is SARS so severe?

The SARS virus infected a total of 8,098 people worldwide, which is not too high, but 774 of them died, and the fatality rate is close to 10% , which is quite high. Why is SARS so severe? Answer this question in three ways:

1. The ultimate goal of the virus is not to kill the host, it just wants to use the host to copy itself, and then spread out. But when a virus replicates itself, it takes up precious resources of the host, and when it spreads, it often destroys the host's cells, both of which can make the host sick, so the disease of the host is a by-product of how the virus completes its life cycle.

The SARS virus, for example, invades human respiratory epithelial cells and uses them to replicate viral RNA and produce protein shells. When the new virus is assembled, it breaks through the Cell Membrane and escapes, leading to the massive death of respiratory epidermal cells, which is why SARS patients experience a sore throat.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On June 11,2003, two medical workers dressed in SARS protective clothing carried a patient from an ambulance at Toronto General Hospital in Canada.

2. There was once a popular theory of infectious disease, to the effect that if a virulent virus infects a host, the longer the infection lasts, the weaker the virus becomes, and eventually a compromise must be reached, into a mutually beneficial symbiosis. But subsequent research has shown that this theory is not entirely correct, and that there are many counterexamples that can not be used to explain all the cases.

In fact, the degree of virulence has a lot to do with the mode of transmission of the virus. For example, viruses that are spread by mosquito bites are most likely to incapacitate their hosts for mosquito bites, so they tend to be highly virulent and leave patients bedridden. Water-borne viruses, for example, often cause severe diarrhea in patients, spreading out of the host body through feces and contaminating water near where they live. Respiratory Infections, by contrast, which are spread by sneezing droplets, tend to be less severe, because the virus needs a mobile host to help it spread, and if it smashes the host down, it can not spread itself.

If so, why is the SARS virus, which spreads mainly by droplets, still so virulent? One reason is that humans also have a special transmission channel, that is the sickbed and hospital. Humans have a tradition of caring for sick people that most animals do not have, so many human viruses have learned to use this to spread. In fact, the SARS virus is the most important route of transmission of hospitals and homes, patients bedridden but the spread of the virus is beneficial.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On May 15,2003, the medical staff of Beijing Xiaotangshan Hospital saw off the recovered SARS patients.

3. But the most important reason is that SARS is a new virus for humans, and is likely to be resisted by the human immune system. But the immune system is a double-edged sword, prone to overreaction. In fact, a significant number of SARS patients died from immune system overreaction, such as acute respiratory distress syndrome and multiple organ dysfunction syndrome caused by Cytokine Storm.

Why does the immune system overreact? The answer is probably still evolutionary. For a dense group, if one of them is infected with a viral infection, the best way is to control the spread of the virus at all costs, rather than keeping the individual alive, so the immune system's response to a viral infection is to maintain the health of the population by killing a thousand people rather than letting one go.

Summary: Whether a new infectious disease is serious or light, whether the process is fast or slow, and the virus's genetic sequence, as well as the patient's immune system, and many other factors, it is difficult to make an accurate prediction in advance. This requires the government's epidemic prevention department to closely monitor the epidemic situation and make an appropriate response as soon as possible. Many countries are still in the exploratory phase in this regard, and lessons need to be learned to prepare for a possible outbreak in the future.

Where's the SARS virus?

After the SARS epidemic, where did the SARS virus go? If it is completely disappeared, why is there a new crown epidemic that is so similar to SARS? Here are three ways to answer the question:

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On May 14,2003, two cold patients attending the fever clinic of Hangzhou Traditional Chinese Medicine Hospital were urgently checking their x-ray films for signs of lung infection.

1. As I said before, RNA viruses are not stable enough to survive long in their hosts, so the SARS virus has indeed disappeared from the world, leaving only a handful of virus labs with samples.

But why does the common cold virus, also known as an RNA virus, still circulate in people? This is because the common cold virus (including many) has a very high mutation rate, which allows it to evade the immune system and move from person to person all year round. In addition, the symptoms of the common cold are very mild, indicating that these viruses have been circulating among humans for a long time, and the human immune system has adapted to these viruses and will not launch severe attacks against them, so these viruses live longer.

A few RNA viruses, such as the Hepatitis C virus, live long in host cells for a variety of unknown reasons. Because there are only a few examples of this, I won't discuss it again.

One might ask, HIV is also an RNA virus, why does HIV live so long? The answer is that HIV is a special Retrovirus virus that converts RNA INTO DNA and integrates it into the host's genome to avoid attack by the immune system. It's an evolutionary strategy, because HIV is sexually transmitted, and it has to wait until the host changes sexual partners before it can spread, so the best strategy for HIV is to bide its time, rather than racing to replicate itself once the infection is successful, making the host ill quickly.

In addition, it is because HIV's life cycle contains both RNA and DNA that the virus can easily mutate, making it difficult to develop a vaccine, but also long-term hiding in the host cell to escape the host's immune system.

2. Now that the SARS virus has completely disappeared from human society, then where did the new coronavirus come from? The answer is bats. This is the natural host of coronaviruses, which can live permanently in bats and cross-infect and pass between different bat populations. Over time, the bat population has developed an unusually large and complex gene pool of coronaviruses, which contains a wide variety of viral sequences and is still in flux. Once a type of mutation happens to match a receptor in a human cell, it can infect the body and cross species. That's how the SARS virus came to be, and that's how the new coronaviruses come to be.

A parallel is the flu virus. The virus usually hides mainly in birds, but a small number of viruses in pigs as the natural host, which we have often heard of bird flu and swine flu. The flu viruses that live in birds and pigs are constantly mutating and looking to invade, much like coronaviruses.

Known collectively as "Zoonosis" , they are a dangerous new form of infectious disease in modern society. These viruses (bacteria) usually hide in animals, constantly carrying out gene mutation and gene recombination, looking for opportunities to invade human beings.

Human beings are the ideal host for the virus: First, human activities are wide, spread all over the world, the virus is easy to spread quickly with human help (such as SARS virus on a plane to spread quickly to the world) ; Humans are very large in number and weight, and can carry far more viruses than most animals. The only problem is that humans understand science, and execution is very strong, so SARS virus only happy a few days before the human extinction.

It must be pointed out that in the case of SARS, mankind's luck is very good. SARS has only one intermediate host, the famous civet cat. Fortunately, the civet cat is neither a rare animal nor a pet, with the state order, the civet cat trading market closed, SARS virus will have nowhere to hide.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 6,2004, Guangzhou Forest Public Security Police seized 86 masked palm civets at Xinyuan Wholesale Poultry and livestock market.

The Saudis, by contrast, are not so lucky. Because the Middle East virus (Mers) intermediate host is camels, the local people can not kill all camels, so the virus is still alive in camels, waiting for the opportunity to continue to spread to humans.

Why do animals carry certain viruses for so long without getting sick? That's actually a bogus question. I've read a lot of articles extolling the virtues of bats. Bats are amazing creatures. They tolerate viruses much better than other mammals, but that doesn't mean they don't get sick. In fact, we don't know how much damage the virus is doing to bats, which may be suffering from the virus on a daily basis, much like their second cousins who got swine flu.

In any case, most humans don't really care about this. What we care about is whether the viruses that live in animal populations can have genetic mutations that affect humans, and whether those mutations can be passed on to humans. If that happens, the result will be a disaster, because the human immune system will react violently to a new virus for the first time, just as it did with SARS. Remember, most people who die from SARS don't die from the virus itself, but from the immune system's overreaction to the virus.

3. How on earth can we avoid zoonosis? One obvious answer is not to eat wild animals. If we had not eaten civet cats, there would not have been that SARS epidemic.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 10,2004, who staff visited the wildlife market in Guangzhou to see if any civet cats were still being sold.

Of the more than 300 new infections reported between 1940 and 2004,60.3 percent were caused by zoonosis, 71.8 percent by wild animals and less than a third by domestic animals, according to a 2008 paper in nature.

But, more than keeping your mouth shut, it's keeping your legs shut. Most of the direct contact between humans and wild animals takes place in the wild. What is said here is by no means only tourism, but more often, human beings, in order to survive, constantly expand their territory and encroach on the territory of wild animals, that's where most of the zoonosis from the wild comes from.

The bottom line: Even if we control our mouths and our legs, there is no guarantee that all zoonosis will be eliminated, because today's humans simply can not avoid direct and indirect contact with wild animals. For example, bird flu and swine flu are transmitted to humans through poultry and livestock. How can we not raise chickens and pigs? Cats and dogs may also be intermediate hosts to some mysterious virus, so should we kill cats and dogs for it?

Therefore, the zoonosis is unavoidable, such as SARS and the new crown, such as infectious diseases will certainly break out many times in the future, we can only spread knowledge of infectious diseases through various channels, and raise citizens'awareness of prevention, at the same time, we will vigorously develop a national-led epidemic prevention system, speed up the development of specific drugs and vaccines, and actively respond to the challenges from nature.
